<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871211-0092 </DOCNO><HL> U.S. Closes 5 BanksIn Louisiana, Texas</HL><DD> 12/11/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Regulators closed five banks in Texas and Louisiana, bringing the number of bank failures nationwide this year to 178, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.    The closed banks were Heritage National Bank, Austin, Texas, with assets of $50 million; BancFirst-Austin, Austin, with assets of $23.7 million; First National Bank in Rhome, Rhome, Texas, with assets of $9.4 million; Louisiana Bank andamp; Trust Co., Crowley, La., with assets of $17.9 million; and American Bank in Louisiana, Morgan City, La., with assets of $16.4 million.    All were scheduled to reopen today as branches of banks that acquired them with FDIC assistance.    Heritage National's office opens as a branch of Community National Bank, Austin, which is due to assume its $48.4 million in deposits.    BancFirst-Austin becomes a branch of Texas Capital Bank-Fort Bend, Richmond, Texas, which assumes its $23.7 million in deposits.    Louisiana Bank andamp; Trust's office becomes a branch of Evangeline Bank andamp; Trust Co., Ville Platt, La., which is assuming its $20.2 million in deposits and much of its assets.    American Bank's office reopens as a branch of the St. Mary Bank andamp; Trust Co., Franklin, La., which assumes its $15.7 million in deposits and much of its assets.    The First National Bank in Rhome becomes an office of Continental State Bank, Boyd, Texas, which takes over its $9.4 million in deposits. </TEXT></DOC>